In order to re- moue all the difficulty from this passage I formerly proposed an emenda- tion, namely a medioque ubique lantundem absit extremum, striking out quantum idem a summo, which is only found in a single Ms. in the mar- gin. 1 mention this here only to controvert a somewhat prevalent miscon- ception. Because Cicero, Sallust and the older authors in general only use ubique in passages where a relative or interrogative pronoun precedes, qui ubique and the like, and because it very osten seems as if ubique in such passages were equivalent to et uhi, Lachmann, Lucret. IV, 638, p. 251, has stated with his usual confidence that in the older language and even in Cicero's time ubique could nowhere be used in any other sense, and that it was a gross imperilia to suppose that it could as well be used in the same manner as the other words compounded with the indefinite que, undi- que, usque, ulerque ἃς. (a usage which still occurs in Horace, eg. Sat. 11, 5, 23). The fact in regard to Cicero and the older writers had been ob- servcd by others long before Lachmann ; cf. Duker De Latinit. Vett. 1.
